{"title_page": "Mike Singleton", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Mike Singleton\n| image       = Mike Singleton 2005.jpg\n| caption     = Mike Singleton in San Diego, California in 2005\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = 21 February 1951\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = 10 October 2012 (aged 61)\n| death_place = [[Switzerland]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2012/10/16/farewell-to-british-gaming-design-legend-mike-singleton/|title=Farewell To British Game Design Legend Mike Singleton|last=Rossignol|first=Jim|date=16 October 2012|publisher=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|accessdate=16 October 2012}}</ref>\n| residence   = \n| other_names = \n| known_for   = ''[[The Lords of Midnight]]''<br>''[[Doomdark's Revenge]]''<br>''[[Midwinter (video game)|Midwinter]]''\n| education   = \n| employer    = Cheshire Education Authority<br />Postern Software<br />PetSoft<br />Beyond Software<br />[[Krome Studios Melbourne|Melbourne House]]<br />[[Telecomsoft#Rainbird Rainbird Software|Rainbird Software]]<br />Simon & Schuster Interactive<br />Mirage Software<br />[[Microprose]]\n| occupation  = Computer programmer\n| title       = \n| salary      = \n| networth    = \n| height      = \n| weight      = \n| term        = \n| predecessor = \n| successor   = \n| party       = \n| boards      = \n| religion    = \n| spouse      = \n| partner     = \n| children    = \n| parents     = \n| relatives   = \n| signature   = \n| website     = \n| footnotes   = \n}}\n\n'''Mike Singleton''' (21 February 1951&nbsp;\u2013 10 October 2012) was a British [[video game designer]] who wrote various well-regarded titles for the [[ZX Spectrum]] during the 1980s.  His titles include ''[[The Lords of Midnight]]'', ''[[Doomdark's Revenge]]'', ''[[Dark Sceptre]]'', ''[[War in Middle Earth (1988 video game)|War in Middle Earth]]'' and ''[[Midwinter (video game)|Midwinter]]''.  Before developing video games, Singleton was an English teacher in [[Ellesmere Port]], Cheshire, England.\n\n==Early work==\nSingleton originally started programming in the late 1970s, and writing ''Computer Race'', a horse racing game he designed for a betting shop on the [[Commodore PET]].<ref name=crash14>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.crashonline.org.uk/14/singletn.htm |title=I BET TOLKIEN DID THE SAME |work=[[Crash (magazine)|Crash]] |date=March 1985 |issue=14}}</ref>  Moving on from this, he began working on [[arcade game]]s for the Pet, working with PetSoft, where he wrote ''Space Ace'' entirely in [[MOS Technology 6502|6502]] [[machine code]].  The game broke sales records of the day by selling three hundred copies.<ref name=crash41>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.crashonline.org.uk/41/maelstrm.htm |title=MAELSTROM IN A TEACUP |work=Crash |date=June 1987 |issue=41}}</ref>\n\nSingleton's association with PetSoft turned out to be short-lived, as PetSoft, who had been due to enter into a contract with [[Sinclair Research Ltd.|Sinclair Research]] in [[Cambridge]] to write software for the new [[Sinclair ZX80|ZX80]], lost out on the deal to [[Psion (computers)|Psion]].  Singleton contacted British inventor and entrepreneur [[Clive Sinclair]] and was asked to send his games along.<ref name=crash41 />  He was then asked to visit the site in Cambridge, and invited to work on software for their brand new [[Sinclair ZX81|ZX81]] micro.<ref name=crash14 />\n\nSingleton used this as the platform for his ''GamesPack1'' project. ''GamesPack1'' was a series of games, each fitting into just 1 [[kilobyte]] of memory.  It was one of the first commercial software programs written for the ZX81, and something of a runaway success, selling a massive 90,000 copies, earning Singleton [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]6,000 for his efforts,<ref name=crash41 /> having taken him just two weeks over the Christmas holidays to complete.<ref name=crash14 />\n\n==Golden age of the home microcomputer==\nWhilst the arcade game writing business was making him a living, Singleton, who retired from teaching completely in 1982 to become a full-time freelance [[video game designer|games designer]], was always an old school war gamer at heart,<ref name=sua85>{{cite magazine |url=https://archive.org/stream/sinclair-user-magazine-annual-1985/SinclairUser-Annual1985#page/n37/mode/2up |title=Chapter 4: Hit Squad |work=The 1985 Sinclair User Annual |publisher=[[Sinclair User]] |date=1985 |pages=39\u201342}}</ref> hooked from an early age on war [[board game]]s and [[Play-by-mail game|play-by-mail]] (PBM) strategy gaming, working for a time on ''Seventh Empire'', a PBM game he put together for ''[[Computer and Video Games (magazine)|Computer and Video Games]]'' magazine (''C&VG''),<ref name=sua85 /> which eventually led to [[Beyond Software]] when ''C&VG'' editor Terry Pratt moved to run Beyond.<ref name=crash14 />\n\nIn March 1984, Singleton's spy-themed board game, ''Treachery'', which had its complicated game logic controlled by a computer program, was featured in ''C&VG'', with a type-in listing for the Spectrum, together with a keyboard overlay (a common feature of his games), centre-spread board and a set of counters.  The game was so popular among the readers that the editor asked for conversions for the [[Commodore 64]] and [[BBC Micro]] to be produced, and each of them featured in ''C&VG'''s 1985 yearbook.\n\nIt was from Beyond that Singleton, who remained freelance, was by September 1983 being pressed for more programs, and having progressed to the Sinclair ZX Spectrum, he wrote what are widely regarded as some of the best strategy adventure games ever to be seen on those early home microcomputers,<ref name=\"PlanSinc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nvg.ntnu.no/sinclair/industry/programmers/mikesingleton.htm |title=Planet Sinclair: The Sinclair Industry: Programmers: Mike Singleton |website=Nvg.ntnu.no |date= |accessdate=2016-06-27}}</ref> the ''Midnight'' series: ''[[Lords of Midnight]]'' (released in July 1984) and ''[[Doomdark's Revenge]]'', which were originally intended to form the first two episodes in a trilogy of which, the final episode, ''[[Eye of the Moon]]'', never came about. Each of the two games played out on a scale never seen before back in the mid-eighties, at a time when many games were boasting 50 or even 100 locations, ''Lords of Midnight'''s groundbreaking gameplay featured over 4,000 locations, and ''Doomdark's Revenge'', 6,000, plus well in excess of 100 player controllable characters.  Had ''Eye of the Moon'' come to fruition, it was to have had around 24,000 locations, in a map featuring twelve distinct regions, each with a local sub-quest completely separate from the main objective of the game.<ref name=crash41 />\n\nMoving on from the ''Midnight'' series, Singleton worked on several games of a more arcade-like nature, the first of which, ''[[Throne of Fire]]'',<ref name=\"PlanSinc\" /> a side viewed live action game, featured a multiplayer option where each player used the same computer to explore simultaneously, each trying to complete a set of objectives which lead to the overall completion of the game. ''[[Dark Sceptre]]'',<ref name=\"PlanSinc\" /> released later the same year, was also in essence a sideways viewed live action game, but returned to a more adventure-like feel, with a long, drawn out challenge awaiting the player who would need to build up their forces to consolidate their position before seizing on the opportunity to actually complete the game.\n\nTwo years later, ''[[War in Middle-earth]]'',<ref name=\"PlanSinc\" /> whilst essentially an [[adventure game]] on a similar scale to the ''Midnight'' series, represented a switch from the adventure to an action philosophy, requiring the player to interact with the characters under their control directly, moving them individually in each of the battles,<ref name=crash41 /> giving the game much more of an arcade/adventure feel.\n\n==Later work==\nIn the late 1980s, Singleton moved onto the [[16-bit]] machines that were making an appearance, and worked on the classic ''[[Midwinter (video game)|Midwinter]]'' trilogy, also producing another work in the ''Lords of Midnight'' series in 1995, [[Lords of Midnight: The Citadel]].\n\nIn the 21st century, Singleton continued working in games design, making him one of a few developers to have made the transition to more modern consoles from the early days of home computing. Singleton worked for [[Midas Interactive]] and [[LucasArts]] on several games for the [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]] and [[PlayStation]] consoles, such as the action games ''[[HyperSonic Xtreme]]'' and ''[[Indiana Jones and the Emperor's Tomb]]''. Singleton worked on the strategy game ''[[Wrath Unleashed]]'', with his latest productions being ''[[Gauntlet: Seven Sorrows]]'', a continuation of the 80s arcade classic ''[[Gauntlet (arcade game)|Gauntlet]]'' series of games, and ''[[Race Driver: Grid]]'', a racing game developed by [[Codemasters]].<ref>{{moby developer|id=17924|name=Singleton's profile}}</ref> At the time of his death after suffering from cancer,<ref>{{Citation | title = RIP Mike Singleton, the RPG visionary who revolutionised the genre | url = https://www.theguardian.com/technology/gamesblog/2012/oct/16/mike-singleton-rpg-visionary-games | publisher = theguardian.com | last = Stuart | first = Keith | date = 16 October 2012 | accessdate = 30 November 2019}}</ref> Singleton was working on an iPhone port of ''Lords of Midnight''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icemark.com/blog/archives/2012/10/16/night-has-fallen/ |title=Night has fallen...|last=Wild|first=Jon|website=Icemark.com|date=16 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==List of games==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ 8-bit titles\n|-\n! style=\"width:225px;\"|Title\n! style=\"width:180px;\"|Distributor\n! Year\n! style=\"width:140px;\"|Platform\n|-\n| ''Space Ace''\n| PetSoft\n| 1981\n| [[Commodore PET|PET]]\n|-\n| ''GamesPack1''\n| Sinclair Research Ltd\n| 1981\n| [[Sinclair ZX81|ZX81]]\n|-\n| ''Shadowfax''\n| Postern\n| 1982\n| [[BBC Micro|BBC]], [[Commodore 64|C64]]/VIC-20, [[ZX Spectrum|Spectrum]]\n|-\n| ''Siege''\n| Postern\n| 1983\n| PET/C64/VIC-20, Spectrum\n|-\n| ''Snake Pit''\n| Postern\n| 1983\n| C64/PET/VIC-20, Spectrum\n|-\n| ''3-Deep Space''\n| Postern\n| 1983\n| C64/VIC-20, Spectrum\n|-\n| ''[[The Lords of Midnight]]''\n| [[Beyond Software]]\n| 1984\n| [[Amstrad CPC|Amstrad]], C64, Spectrum\n|-\n| ''[[Doomdark's Revenge]]''\n| Beyond\n| 1985\n| Amstrad, C64, Spectrum\n|-\n| ''[[Quake Minus One]]''\n| [[Beyond Software]]\n| 1985\n| C64\n|-\n| ''[[Dark Sceptre]]''\n| Beyond Software\n| 1986\n| Spectrum\n|-\n| ''[[Throne of Fire]]''\n| [[Krome Studios Melbourne|Melbourne House]]\n| 1987\n| Amstrad, C64, Spectrum\n|-\n| ''[[War in Middle Earth (1988 video game)|War in Middle Earth]]''\n| Melbourne House\n| 1988\n| Spectrum\n|-\n| ''[[Star Trek: The Rebel Universe]]''\n| [[Firebird Software]]\n| 1988\n| C64\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ 16-bit titles\n|-\n! style=\"width:225px;\"|Title\n! style=\"width:180px;\"|Distributor\n! Year\n! style=\"width:140px;\"|Platform\n|-\n| ''Star Trek: The Rebel Universe''\n| Simon & Schuster Interactive\n| 1987\n| [[Atari ST]], [[Personal computer|PC]]\n|-\n| ''[[Space Cutter]]''\n| Melbourne House\n| 1987\n| Amiga\n|-\n| ''War in Middle Earth''\n| Melbourne House\n| 1988\n| Atari ST, Amiga, PC\n|-\n| ''Whirligig''\n| Firebird Software\n| 1988\n| Atari ST, Amiga\n|-\n| ''[[Midwinter (video game)|Midwinter]]''\n| Rainbird Software\n| 1989\n| Atari ST, Amiga, PC\n|-\n| ''[[Flames of Freedom]]''\n| [[MicroProse]]\n| 1990\n| Atari ST, Amiga, PC\n|-\n| ''[[Grimblood]]''\n| Virgin Interactive\n| 1990\n| Atari ST, Amiga\n|-\n| ''[[Ashes of Empire|Ashes of Empire/Fallen Empire]]''\n| Mirage\n| 1991\n| Atari ST, Amiga, PC\n|-\n| ''[[Starlord (video game)|Starlord]]''\n| MicroProse\n| 1993\n| Atari ST, Amiga, PC\n|-\n| ''[[Lords of Midnight: The Citadel]]''\n| [[Domark]]\n| 1995\n| PC\n|-\n| ''The Ring Cycle''\n| [[Psygnosis]]\n| 1995\n| PC\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Console titles\n|-\n! style=\"width:225px;\"|Title\n! style=\"width:180px;\"|Distributor\n! Year\n! style=\"width:140px;\"|Platform\n|-\n| ''[[HSX: HyperSonic Xtreme]]''\n| [[Midas Interactive Entertainment]]\n| 2002\n| [[PlayStation]]\n|-\n| ''[[Indiana Jones and the Emperor's Tomb]]''\n| [[LucasArts]]\n| 2003\n| [[Macintosh|Mac]], PC, [[PlayStation 2|PS2]], [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]]\n|-\n| ''[[Wrath Unleashed]]''\n| LucasArts\n| 2004\n| PS2, Xbox\n|-\n| ''[[Gauntlet: Seven Sorrows]]''\n| [[Midway Home Entertainment]]\n| 2005\n| PS2, Xbox\n|-\n| ''[[Race Driver: Grid]]''\n| [[Codemasters]]\n| 2008\n| PC, [[PlayStation 3|PS3]], [[Xbox 360]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20161012234736/http://wiki.icemark.com/index.php?title=Mike_Singleton Icemark.com Wiki page on Singleton]\n* [http://www.midnightmu.com Midnight/MU \u2013 A browser-based multiplayer game based on The Lords of Midnight/Doomdarks Revenge]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Singleton, Mike}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:Schoolteachers from Cheshire]]\n[[Category:British video game designers]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:MicroProse people]]\n[[Category:People from Ellesmere Port]]\n[[Category:Video game producers]]\n[[Category:Video game programmers]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Mike Singleton\n| image       = Mike Singleton 2005.jpg\n| caption     = Mike Singleton in San Diego, California in 2005\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = 21 February 1951\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = 10 October 2012 (aged 61)\n| death_place = [[Switzerland]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2012/10/16/farewell-to-british-gaming-design-legend-mike-singleton/|title=Farewell To British Game Design Legend Mike 